                  "motivation": "commenting",
                  "body": {
                    "type": "TextualBody",
                    "value": "<p>get them to make a new move in the matter,<lb/> let them have the\n                                        honor and the glory of<lb/> reviving the subject, something\n                                        must be<lb/> done.</p>\n                              <p rend=\"indent(1)\">“Our Ritual and its Recital” has claimed<lb/> much\n                                        notice here as also <persName>Mr Eckman's</persName>\n                                        ar-<lb/>ticle, they contain stubborn facts and they<lb/>\n                                        must be remedied, I often wished that<lb/> some reformation\n                                        could be made in the<lb/> recital of our ritual, my\n                                        principal, and<lb/> instructions that I have invariably\n                                        given<lb/> to our hazanim here has been, “that<lb/> every\n                                        portion of the device that is read<lb/> in the synagogue\n                                        should be read in<lb/> a slow, distinct and impressive\n                                        manner<lb/> irregardless of the time that it occupies,”<lb/>\n                                        if the Form of Service is too long for to be<lb/> recited in\n                                        that manner in reasona-<lb/>ble length of time, steps should\n                                        be taken<lb/> to have them curtailed by omitting all<lb/>\n                                        <sic>repititions</sic>, The Catholics have their<lb/> “Three\n                                        hail Mary's &amp;c” it is not necessary<lb/> for us to have\n                                        these repetitions.</p>\n                              <p rend=\"indent(1)\">Only look at the Kipur service where<lb/>\n                                                  “<add>?</add>” are repeated so often. “El\n                                        Meleck<lb/> yosheb” is rattled away ridiculous and<lb/> so\n                                        it goes through the whole of the ser-<lb/>vice the Question\n                                        arises, how are our<lb/> children to learn to say their\n                                        prayers</p>"
                  },
                  "target": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p3959ct64/canvas/p2"
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
